What is Dash?

Dash is a framework for building analytical web apps

Dash is a Python framework.

You can use it do create web sites with interactive charts and graphs. All the common chart types

  • line graphs
  • bar charts and
  • heat maps

are supported.

It's pretty cool and differentiates it self from other charting libraries with the motto:

No JavaScript required.

No JavaScript required.

And, indeed, Dash makes it possible to express everything for a dashboard-type of web app in pure Python.

We will soon see how this is done, but let's first get an impression what's possible with Dash. Web pages made with Dash can look like this:

This is the screenshot of a dashboard for an financial index fund.

Dash can look like this:

Here you see a site visualising the number of traffic accidents in the UK.

And finally Dash can do this

This dashboard shows you all the sightings of "bigfoot" in the US.

How does Dash do all of this? Like many powerful tools it's "standing on the shoulders of giants", in this case three software libraries:

Plotly

  • (Plotly Express)

First Plotly. It is a pretty powerful charting library written in its core in JavaScript, but with comprehensive Python bindings, because it is made by the same people as Dash. Plotly itself utilises underneath the SVG graphing library D3.

Plotly does all the drawing of the charts and provides the built-in interactivity.

CLICK

In the live demo we'll use a particular extension module of Plotly called Plotly Express. It makes the Plotly configuration a snap.

React

The next giant is React. React is the layer for the custom interactivity in Dash apps.

It is a JavaScript library for web UIs and it enables Dash to build effective single-page websites.

Flask

Finally Flask. This is the web framework Dash employs.

Flask is a Python package which calls itself a "micro framework" because it is fairly light-weight. This makes it a great fit for Dash.

Essentially every Dash site is a Flask app.

All these three components are managed and accessed by Dash:

  • Plotly
  • React
  • Flask
  • Dash

Small applications don't need to call into internal components. In practice though you might need to call at least into the Plotly interface to tweak some visualisation aspects.

In the live demo we will make use of an additional package, Panda. It is not part of the Dash Eco system, but will provide the data in the app.

CLICK

Dash can leverage the power of Plotly via the figure objects. We instantiated a figure object through one call to Plotly Express.

CLICK

For interactive components Dash uses the @app.callback decorator. When we apply this decorator to a function, then we can do in this function all drawing updates according to changes in the UI.

This was a brief peek into what Dash offers...

So far this talk might sound a bit like an ad campaign for Dash -- well it is not:

  • Challenges
  • Multi-page sites awkward to code
  • Rendering can be slow...

We discovered difficulties with our use case.

CLICK

This is only a minor issue but because Dash is geared towards single-page apps it needs additional effort to distribute the charts over multiple pages. So for multi-page app don't expect much help from Dash.

CLICK

More complex Dash apps load a tad slow, because (from my understanding) the JavaScript engine in the browser does a lot of translating of the Python code. Normally that's not a problem, but when you have very slow JavaScript engines (like in IT infrastructures with virtualised desktops) it really shows.

This can be a deal breaker. In our particular environment with virtualised desktops it was a deal breaker. So for the dashboard we did not continue with a Python solution, rather opted for one of the many JavaScript charting libraries, wiring the controls "manually" in JavaScript.

Anyway...

Wrap it up

Let's wrap up our dip into Dash.

What is Dash good for?

Dash builds beautiful
analytical web apps

Dash is a great Python framework you can use to build beautiful data visualization websites.

What sets it apart?

Pure Python. No JavaScript required. Really.

The whole API is accessible in pure Python. Even component callbacks for custom interactivity you can write and manage in Python.

What are the challenges?

Browser speed critical for
end-user experience

Dash sites can be rather slow to render (depending on how fast the Javascript engine of the rendering browser is)

Dash is fun!
